master.notes: Final product of the PledgeMusic project "New African Project 'Bloody Rain'", launched early December, 2013.Available as various bundles, ranging from a simple download (including both mp3 and FLAC) at £8, to "Concert In Your Living Room Anywhere in Europe" £2,500.Available exclusively from PledgeMusic - until general release on September 15, 2014."I have teamed up with PledgeMusic to record and release my new album Bloody Rain. An album influenced by African, European and North and South American rhythms, melodies and musicians. The subject matter is widespread also: love, loss, childhood, homophobia, contraception, honour killings, child soldiers, corruption, greed, fear and freedom. The songs celebrate humanity while issuing an urgent call to action to right the wrongs suffered by so many. Above all, the album is about the redemptive power of love.The great thing about this way of making music is I can include you, the fans, in the whole process. Through the recording, the mixing and mastering right through to a special live presentation of the album for pledgers only at London’s Hippodrome in June 2014. As part of the process we have teamed up with Annie Lennox’s SING charity to raise money [10% of pledge goal] for their campaign ‘A voice for HIV/Aids Women and Children’."[compiled from pledgemusic.com]All bundles include project updates published online during the pledge period. 15 updates were published which include 4 downloadable MP3's:– "Wild Flowers", 4:54 mins, 192 kbps - different mix– "I Shall Be Released", 6:28 mins, 128 kbps - live version– "Come Christmas, Come Love", 2:48 mins, 160 kbps - from the 2009 "Angels At Christmas" EP– "Gay Man Blues", credited to Sarah Jane and the Fallen Angel Band, 6:30 mins, 160 kbps - live version, retitled "Get Them Out" on the albumA video clip of the recording of "Coal Train" was also made available via live stream.

master.notes: This was Rollins' last album before industry pressures led him to take a six year hiatus. The album represents one of his more notable experiments with free jazz, and according to [i] The New Grove Dictionary of Jazz [/i] illustrates "the furthest extent to which he incorporated noise elements into his playing". Music journalist Piero Scaruffi praised the album for the dissonant titular song, "a bold thematic improvisation on the riff of Lionel Hampton's 'Hey Baba Rebop'."Initially released on Impulse! Records, the album has been reissued many times on CD and LP by Impulse!, MCA, Universal International and GRP.Personnel:Sonny Rollins (tenor sax); Elvin Jones (drums); Jimmy Garrison (bass); Freddie Hubbard (trumpet on "East Broadway Run Down" only)
